CS 184 Final Report: Team Shaders
ARTHUR POMMERSHEIM, NICOLAS VEGA, TONY LI, and MYA THANEGI SOE
Fig. 1. Team Shader Logo
This project involves creating a new collection of GLSL fractal shaders. It highlights the vast potential of shader programming,
illustrating how intricate visuals can be generated from simple geometric primitives.
Additional Key Words and Phrases: shaders
ACM Reference Format:
Arthur Pommersheim, Nicolas Vega, Tony Li, and Mya Thanegi Soe. 2024. CS 184 Final Report: Team Shaders. 1, 1 (May 2024), 10 pages.

1 INTRODUCTION
Shaders provide a method for rendering realistic and captivating imagery. Shaders have continued to evolve, starting as
simple programs for rudimentary rendering to complex porgrams that can render and simulate physical phenomena.
This project seeks to explore the capabilities of shaders.

By adjusting geometric properties, surface materials, and lighting techniques, our team has successfully developed a
variety of visually distinct fractal shaders. Initially, our shaders were designed to render basic geometries using at
colors and straightforward lighting. Building on this foundation, we have expanded our scope to incorporate complex
elements like the Mandelbulb set, employing advanced concepts such as HSV color models and Blinn-Phong lighting.
This progression has allowed us to achieve richer, more intricate visual outputs.

2.2 Raymarching
In order to render the Mandelbulb in 3D space in a time-ecient manner, the technique of raymarching is used. The
basic setup is the same as standard raytracing, where a ray is sent out from the camera in a certain direction, looking
for intersections with objects in the scene. Raymarching modies the ray intersection process by instead following the
path of the ray guided by the distance between the closest object in the scene and the current position along the ray.
Specically, this distance is calculated using a signed distance function (SDF) which is made for each object in the
scene. If this distance is less than a chosen small threshold, then this is counted as an intersection. If this distance is
greater than a suciently large, chosen threshold, then the ray position is considered to be too far from any of the
objects in the scene and counts as a ray miss. Otherwise, the current position along the ray is incremented by traveling
along the ray the same amount as the distance given by the SDF and this process is repeated.

number of iterations of the Mandelbrot function using the methods described earlier, ending iteration early if the point

2.2.3 HSV to RGB Conversion. Our team implemented a function that converts a color from HSV (Hue, Saturation,
Value) format to RGB (Red, Green, Blue) format [
5
]. The HSV representation of color was chosen in order to provide
the ability to rotate hue around the color wheel.
The function begins by extracting the hue (H), saturation (S), and value (V) from the input HSV vector. It calculates the
chroma (C), which represents the intensity of the color, and determines which sector of the color wheel the hue belongs
to. We calculate an intermediate value X to determine the second largest component of this color. The conditional
statements use the location in the color wheel to set the appropriate color value. We then adjust all three RGB variables
by m to match the "value" portion.

2.4 Fog
The linear interpolation method based on distance for rendering fog involves gradually blending the color of objects
with the fog color as their distance from the viewer increases. This technique uses a simple mathematical formula to
compute the intensity of fog based on the object’s distance from the camera. The further the object, the more it blends
with the fog color, eectively simulating the eect of atmospheric scattering. The fog amount is then linear interpolated
with the other objects in the scene.

2.5 Minor Eects: Texture Mapping + Glow + Shadow
We used the texture method in GLSL to apply a texture to anytime the raymarched rays exceed the max threshold and
misses.
Glow eects in visualizations can be enhanced by adjusting the color intensity based on the number of ray steps
used in rendering. Points that are closer to a fractal often require more ray steps to determine their visibility, even if
they do not directly intersect with the fractal. This method ensures that pixels near the object exhibit a glow, subtly
emphasizing their proximity to the fractal boundaries and enhancing the overall visual appeal of the scene.
The computation of soft shadows was achieved adjusting the rate at which shadow hardness changes based on the
distance to obstructing objects. This results in shadows that soften gradually with distance, mimicking natural light
behavior more closely. This calculation is done during the raymarching process.

2.6 Problems encountered and Lessons Learned
In implementing the Mandelbrot shader code, our team gleaned several valuable insights. First, this shader’s iterative
nature underscores the importance of setting appropriate thresholds for computing the set. We also learned about the
mix function which performs a linear interpolation which is integral to how we color the Mandelbrot set shader.
Additionally, implementing the normalization of pixel coordinates taught us about maintaining aspect ratio correct-
ness and visual accuracy across dierent screen resolutions. The incorporation of time-based dynamic transformations,
such as rotation, added a layer of complexity and taught us more about animating shaders in response to time.
We also learned that zooming into the Mandelbrot shader can be very intensive on our computers. After our shader
zoomed enough, our computers would get hot or fans would start to speed up. This is interesting and may be useful to
look at through a ray-tracing perspective in order to nd ways to make the shader more ecient.
One problem we encountered was the coloring of the Mandelbulb shader. We colored it based o the distance the ray
had traveled from the camera position, but were unable to split this value up between 3 dierent numbers to make an
RGB value. We only had one number to color with, so we switched to using HSV, since saturation and value can be
set to constant values while we adjust hue based on the aforementioned distance value. This required us to write a
function to convert from HSV to RGB as GLSL only takes in RGB. sectionResults

3 RESULTS
3.1 Mandelbrot Set
Our team successfully implemented shader code to visualize the Mandelbrot set, a complex fractal structure. The
shader maps each pixel’s coordinates to a point in the complex plane and iteratively applies the Mandelbrot equation
to determine whether the point belongs to the fractal set. By setting a high iteration threshold and adjusting the
coloring based on the number of iterations before the point escapes, our shader eectively highlights the boundaries
and intricate details of the set. The color gradient, from deep blue for points far from the set to vibrant orange for those
closer, provides a clear visual distinction of the fractal’s complex behavior. Additionally, we introduced dynamic visual
elements by enabling rotation based on the elapsed time, enhancing the interactive aspect of our visualization.
Fig. 4. The group’s first two Mandelbrot set Shader results
3.2 Mandelbulb
Our team utilized the raymarching method to visualize the Mandelbulb, a three-dimensional fractal that extends
the concept of the Mandelbrot set into higher dimensions. We rendered each point via iterative processing using
a generalized version of the Mandelbrot formula and signed distance fucntion to determine their inclusion in the
Mandelbulb structure. We set a high iteration limit to ensure precise detailing, with a dynamic color scale highlighting
the fractal’s intricate topology. The visualization is further enhanced by real-time rotation eects, which allow users to
explore the fractal from multiple perspectives, making the experience interactive and engaging.

3.3 Mandelbulb Modifications/Exploration
The Mandelbulb oered a canvas for creativity, and our team seized the opportunity to delve into and experiment with
several of the concepts discussed in the class.
3.3.1 Altering the Nylanders formula. A simple change of sine to cosine in the formula and careful selection of color
results in a central structure that resembles an inferno, with radiant orange and ery red tones that emanate outward
in an explosive array of sharp, spiky forms. [4]
Our team delved into the HSV color model as outlined in our lectures, which empowered us to create a dynamic
Mandelbulb whose colors continuously evolve through the spectrum of the color wheel. This exploration not only
deepened our understanding of color theory but also enhanced the visual impact of our fractal, showcasing a vibrant,
ever-shifting display of hues.
3.3.2 Shading. We also added some lighting eects onto our Mandelbulb in order to add visual air to the scene. We
implemented diuse shading, Blinn Phong shading, as well as fog.

4 OUTSTANDING WORK
The team explored other fractals such as the Quaternion Julia Set, a topic detailed by Crane in his work on ray tracing
these complex structures on GPUs [
2
]. The Quaternion Julia Sets involve complex, four-dimensional shapes that are
projected into 3-D. Although the team was not able to fully implement this in the time available, there is much more
with Shaders to explore.
